{"vocabInfos":[{"lsjDefs":"<b> ἐθέλω</b> <br /> or <b>θέλω</b> (see. below), <i>Epic dialect</i> <i>subjunctive</i> ἐθέλωμι [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 8th c.BC: Ilias Homerus Epicus “Illiad” 1.549, 9.397 \">Refs 8th c.BC+</a>]: <i>imperfect</i> ἤθελον [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 14.120, etc.\">Refs</a>]; <i>Epic dialect</i> and Lyric poetry ἔθελον [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 6.336, 6th c.BC: Theognis Elegiacus 606, 5th c.BC: Bacchylides Lyricus 10.73 \">Refs 6th c.BC+</a>]; <i>Ionic dialect</i> ἐθέλεσκον [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 8th c.BC: Ilias Homerus Epicus “Illiad” 13.106, 5th c.BC: Herodotus Historicus 6.12 \">Refs 8th c.BC+</a>]: <i>future</i> ἐθελήσω [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 8th c.BC: Ilias Homerus Epicus “Illiad” 18.262, etc.; θελήσω 5th c.BC: Antipho Orator 5.99 \">Refs 8th c.BC+</a>]: <i>aorist 1</i> ἠθέλησα [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 5th c.BC: Herodotus Historicus 2.2, etc.\">Refs 5th c.BC+</a>]; <i>Epic dialect</i> ἐθέλησα [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 8th c.BC: Ilias Homerus Epicus “Illiad” 18.396; _imperative_ θέλησον 4th-5th c.BC: Aeschylus Tragicus “Prometheus Vinctus” 783 \">Refs 8th c.BC+</a>]; <i>subjunctive</i> θελήσῃ[<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" [prev. work] 1028, 5th-6th c.BC: Xenophon Historicus “Institutio Cyri (Cyropaedia)” 2.4.19, etc.; _optative_ θελήσαιμι 5th c.BC: Sophocles Tragicus “Oedipus Coloneus” 1133 \">Refs 5th c.BC+</a>]; <i>participle</i> θελήσας [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" [prev. author] “OT” 649 (Lyric poetry)\">Refs</a>]: <i>perfect</i> ἠθέληκα [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 5th-6th c.BC: Xenophon Historicus “Institutio Cyri (Cyropaedia)” 5.2.9, 4th c.BC: Aeschines Orator 2.139, 4th c.BC: Demosthenes Orator 47.5 \">Refs 5th c.BC+</a>]; τεθέληκα (Alexandrian <i>accusative</i> to [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 2nd c.AD: Phrynichus Atticista 307) LXX.Psa.40(41).12, 1st c.BC: Philodemus Gadarensis Epigrammaticus “Rh.” 2.76 5th c.BC: Sophocles Tragicus, 2nd c.AD: Sextus Empiricus Philosophus “adversus Mathematicos” 2.37 \">LXX+5th c.BC+</a>]: <i>pluperfect</i> ἠθελήκει [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 5th-6th c.BC: Xenophon Historicus “Historia Graeca (Hellenica)” 6.5.21; ἐτεθελήκεσαν 2nd-3rd c.AD: Dio Cassius Historicus 44.26 codices (elsewhere ἠθελήκεσαν as 46.47):—θέλω is never found in 8th c.BC: Homerus Epicus or 8th-7th c.BC: Hesiodus Epicus except 8th c.BC: Ilias Homerus Epicus “Illiad” 1.277 (uncertain), ὅττι θέλοιεν 8th c.BC: Odyssea Homerus Epicus “Odyssey” 15.317 as variant (ἅσσ᾽ ἐθέλοιεν 3rd-2nd c.BC: Aristarchus Grammaticus)\">Refs 8th c.BC+</a>], nor in <i>Aeolic dialect</i>; rarely in early <i>Epic dialect</i> and Eleg., θέλοι [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" “hymnus ad Apollinem” 46, θέλει 6th c.BC: Solon Lyricus 27.12 \">Refs 6th c.BC+</a>]; but is found in <i>Ionic dialect</i> Inscrr., [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" “SIG” 45.16 (Halic., 5th c.BC), 1037.7 (Milet., 4th c.BC), and in 7th-6th c.BC(?): Semonides Iambographus 7.13, 6th c.BC: Hipponax Iambographus 22 B, 6th c.BC: Anacreon Lyricus 92 \">Refs 7th c.BC+</a>]:— both forms in codices of [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 5th c.BC: Herodotus Historicus and 5th c.BC: Hippocrates Medicus and in 1st c.AD(?): Heraclitus and 3rd c.AD: Democritus Epigrammaticus, also in 5th c.BC: Pindarus Lyricus and 5th c.BC: Bacchylides Lyricus: Trag. never use ἐθέλω except in augmented forms, ἤθελον, -ησα: Comedy texts never use θέλω except in phrases such as ἢν θεὸς θέλῃ, εἰ θεὸς θέλοι, 5th-6th c.BC: Aristophanes Comicus “Plutus” 347, “Ra.” 533 \">Refs 5th c.BC+</a>], or parodies of Trag.: early <i>Attic dialect</i> Inscrr, have ἐθέλω [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" “IG” 12.6.41, etc., till 3rd c.BC, when θέλω becomes common: _Attic dialect_ Prose writers rarely use θέλω\">Refs 3rd c.BC+</a>] except in phrases such as ἂν θεὸς θέλῃ [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 4th-3rd c.BC: Dinarchus Orator 2.3 \">Refs 4th c.BC+</a>] or after a long vowel, e.g. μὴ θελῆσαι [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 5th c.BC: Thucydides Historicus 5.72, μὴ θελήσας 4th c.BC: Isaeus Orator 8.11, μὴ θέλοντας 5th-6th c.BC: Andocides Orator 1.22, τῷ θέλοντι [prev. author] 4.7, etc.; but θέλω 5th c.BC: Antipho Orator 3.4.3, θελήσουσιν [prev. author] 5.99: in later Gr. θέλω\">Refs 5th c.BC+</a>] is regular except in the augmented forms; ἐθέλω is not found in LXX or NT:—<b>to be willing</b> (of consent rather than desire, see at {βούλομαι} 1), but also generally, <b>wish</b>, [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 8th c.BC: Odyssea Homerus Epicus “Odyssey” 3.324:\">Refs 8th c.BC+</a>] —Constr.: _absolutely_, especially in <i>participle</i>, ἐθέλων ἐθέλουσαν ἀνήγαγεν[<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" [prev. work] 272; εἰ σύ γε σῷ θυμῷ ἐθέλοις 8th c.BC: Ilias Homerus Epicus “Illiad” 23.894; ἀλλά μοι ἤθελε θυμός 8th c.BC: Odyssea Homerus Epicus “Odyssey” 11.566 \">Refs 8th c.BC+</a>]: frequently followed by <i>infinitive</i> <i>present</i> or <i>aorist</i>, <b>wish to</b>.., [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 8th c.BC: Ilias Homerus Epicus “Illiad” 7.364, etc.: with \">Refs 8th c.BC+</a>]<i>infinitive</i> supplied, εἰ δ᾽ ἐθέλεις πεζός (i.e. ἰέναι) [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 8th c.BC: Odyssea Homerus Epicus “Odyssey” 3.324 \">Refs 8th c.BC+</a>]: with <i>accusative</i> et <i>infinitive</i>, <b>wish that</b>.., [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 8th c.BC: Ilias Homerus Epicus “Illiad” 19.274, 5th c.BC: Herodotus Historicus 1.3 \">Refs 8th c.BC+</a>]; rarely followed by ὥστε, [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 5th c.BC: Euripides Tragicus “Hippolytus” 1327: later with ἵνα, NT.Matt.7.12, etc.: not used with _accusative_ only, except when an \">NT+5th c.BC+</a>]<i>infinitive</i> is easily supplied, εὔκηλος τὰ φράζεαι ἅσσ᾽ ἐθέλῃσθα (i.e. φράζεσθαι) [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 8th c.BC: Ilias Homerus Epicus “Illiad” 1.554, compare 9.397, 7.182, 8th c.BC: Odyssea Homerus Epicus “Odyssey” 14.172 \">Refs 8th c.BC+</a>]; σιτέονται δὲ οὐκ ὅσα ἐθέλουσι (i.e. σιτέεσθαι) [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 5th c.BC: Herodotus Historicus 1.71, compare 5th c.BC: Thucydides Historicus 5.50 \">Refs 5th c.BC+</a>]; εἰ καὶ τῆς ἀξίας ἔλαττον ἐθελήσειέ τις (i.e. φράσαι) [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 4th c.AD: Julianus Imperator “Orationes” 1.132a: also with _neuter_ _pronoun_ or \">Refs 4th c.AD+</a>] <i>adjective</i>, τί δὴ θέλω; with what <b>intent</b>? [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 4th-5th c.BC: Aeschylus Tragicus “Prometheus Vinctus” 118. \">Refs 4th c.BC+</a>]<br /><Level3><b>__2</b></Level3> with <i>negative</i>, almost, ={δύναμαι}, as μίμνειν οὐκ ἐθέλεσκον ἐναντίον they <b>cared</b> not to make a stand, i.e. they <b>were</b> un<b>able</b>, [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 8th c.BC: Ilias Homerus Epicus “Illiad” 13.106; οὐδ᾽.. ἤθελε θυμὸς τειρομένοις ἑτάροισιν ἀμυνέμεν 17.702: _metaphorically_ of things, of a stream, οὐδ᾽ ἔθελε προρέειν ἀλλ᾽ ἴσχετο\">Refs 8th c.BC+</a>] <b>would</b> not run on, but stopped,[<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 21.366, compare 8th c.BC: Odyssea Homerus Epicus “Odyssey” 8.223, 316, “hymnus ad Cererem” 45 \">Refs 8th c.BC+</a>]; αὔλειοι δ᾽ ἔτ᾽ ἔχειν οὐκ ἐθέλουσι θύραι [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 6th c.BC: Solon Lyricus 4.28; τὰ δένδρα οὐδέν μ᾽ ἐθέλει διδάσκειν 5th-6th c.BC: Plato Philosophus “Phaedrus” 230d, compare “R.” 370b \">Refs 6th c.BC+</a>] (said to be an <i>Attic dialect</i> use,[<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" Greg.Cor. p.135 5th c.BC: Sophocles Tragicus). \">Refs 5th c.BC+</a>]<br /><Level3><b>__3</b></Level3> <i>participle</i>, ἐθέλων or θέλων <b>willingly, gladly</b>, [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 8th c.BC: Odyssea Homerus Epicus “Odyssey” 3.272, etc. (also πιθοῦ θελήσας 5th c.BC: Sophocles Tragicus “Oedipus Tyrannus” 649 (Lyric poetry))\">Refs 8th c.BC+</a>]; οὐκ ἐθέλων, ={ἀεκών}, [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 8th c.BC: Ilias Homerus Epicus “Illiad” 4.300 \">Refs 8th c.BC+</a>]; with <i>Article</i> like{ὁ βουλόμενος}, <b>whoever will</b>, i.e. <b>any one</b>, [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 5th c.BC: Sophocles Tragicus “Philoctetes” 619, “Aj.” 1146, 5th-6th c.BC: Plato Philosophus “Gorgias” 508c, etc. \">Refs 5th c.BC+</a>]<br /><Level3><b>__4</b></Level3> θέλεις οὐ θέλεις <b>nolens volens</b>, [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 2nd c.AD: Arrianus Historicus “Epicteti Dissertationes” 3.9.16 \">Refs 2nd c.AD+</a>]; θέλει οὐ θέλει[<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" [prev. work] 3.3, 2nd c.AD: Marcus Antoninus Imperator 11.15. \">Refs 2nd c.AD+</a>]<br /><Level3><b>__5</b></Level3> μὴ ἔθελε, with <i>infinitive</i>, <b>do</b> not, [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 8th c.BC: Ilias Homerus Epicus “Illiad” 1.277, 2.247, 5th c.BC: Euripides Tragicus “Fragmenta” 174. \">Refs 8th c.BC+</a>]<br /><Level3><b>__6</b></Level3> εἰ θέλεις if you <b>please</b>, [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 5th c.BC: Sophocles Tragicus “Oedipus Tyrannus” 343. \">Refs 5th c.BC+</a>]<br /><Level3><b>__7</b></Level3> followed by <i>subjunctive</i>, τί σοι θέλεις δῆτ᾽ εἰκάθ; in what <b>wilt</b> thou that I give way to thee? [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\"[prev. work] 651 (Lyric poetry)\">Refs</a>]; θέλεις μείνωμεν αὐτο; [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" [prev. author] “El.” 80. \">Refs</a>]<br /><Level3><b>__8</b></Level3> <b>maintain, hold</b>, with <i>accusative</i> et <i>infinitive</i>, [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 1st-2nd c.AD: Plutarchus Biographus et Philosophus 2.883e, 2nd c.AD: Pausanias Periegeta 1.4.6. \">Refs 1st c.AD+</a>]<br /><Level3><b>__9</b></Level3> <b>delight in, love</b>, ἔν τινι [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" LXX.1Ki.18.22 \">LXX</a>]; τινά[<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\"LXX.Psa.17(18).20 \">LXX</a>]; but οἱ κακῶς τινὰς θέλοντες their ill-<b>wishers,</b> [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" Cat.Codex Astr. 7.234. \">Refs</a>]<br /><Level3><b>__10</b></Level3> <b>ordain, decree</b>, ἠθέλησεν [ὁ ἡγεμὼν] τὸν κίνδυνον τῆς προβολῆς εἶναι πρός τινας [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" “CPR” 20.17 (3rd c.AD), etc. \">Refs 3rd c.AD+</a>]<br /><Level2><b>__II</b></Level2> of inanimate things (compare above [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 1.2), \">Refs</a>]<br /><Level3><b>__II.1</b></Level3> to express a <b>future</b> event, like our <b>will</b> or <b>shall</b>, εἰ ἐθελήσει ἀναβῆναι ἡ τυραννίς [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 5th c.BC: Herodotus Historicus 1.109; εἰ ἐθελήσει ἐκτρέψαι τὸ ῥέεθρον ὁ Νεῖλος [prev. author] 2.11; εἰ θέλει τοι μηδὲν ἀντίξοον καταστῆναι [prev. author] 7.49, compare 5th-6th c.BC: Plato Philosophus “Respublica” 370b, etc.:—in this sense, very rarely of living things, οὐ δοῦναι θέλοι, ={οὐκ ἂν δοίη}, 4th-5th c.BC: Aeschylus Tragicus “Eumenides” 429; εἴπερ.. οὗτός [σ᾽] ἐθέλει κρατῆσαι 5th-6th c.BC: Aristophanes Comicus “Vespae” 536, compare 5th c.BC: Pindarus Lyricus “N.” 7.90, 5th-6th c.BC: Plato Philosophus “Respublica” 375a. \">Refs 5th c.BC+</a>]<br /><Level3><b>__II.2</b></Level3> <b>to be naturally disposed, to be wont</b> or <b>accustomed</b>, with <i>infinitive</i>, συμβάσιες ἰσχυραὶ οὐκ ἐ. συμμένειν [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 5th c.BC: Herodotus Historicus 1.74; μεγάλα πρήγματα μεγάλοισι κινδύνοισι ἐ. καταιρέεσθαι [prev. author] 7.50; αἱ πλευραὶ οὐκ ἐθέλουσιν ἐς τὸ εὐρὺ αὔξεσθαι 5th c.BC: Hippocrates Medicus “περὶ ἄρθρων ἐμβολῆς” 41; οὐκ ἐ. αἱ γνῶμαι.. ὁμοῖαι εἶναι 5th c.BC: Thucydides Historicus 2.89; τοῦτ᾽ ἐνδελεχὲς ἐ. γίγνεσθαι 4th c.BC: Aristoteles Philosophus “Meteorologica” 347a5, compare “Metaphorical” 1013b27, +others\">Refs 5th c.BC+</a>]; οὐ θέλει ζῆν, of premature births, [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" [prev. author] “HA” 575a28. \">Refs</a>]<br /><Level3><b>__II.3</b></Level3> in phrases expressive of meaning, τὸ θέλει σημαίνειν τὸ τέρας [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 5th c.BC: Herodotus Historicus 1.78; τὸ θέλει τὸ ἔπος εἶπαι [prev. author] 6.37; τὸ θέλει τὰ δῶρα λέγειν [prev. author] 4.131 \">Refs 5th c.BC+</a>]; τὸ ἔπος τοῦτο ἐθέλει λέγειν ὡς.. [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" [prev. author] 2.13. \">Refs</a>]<br /><Level3><b>__II.4</b></Level3> τοῦ θέλοντος, ={τοῦ θελήματος}, [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 5th c.BC: Sophocles Tragicus “Oedipus Coloneus” 1220 (Lyric poetry, assuming variant). \">Refs 5th c.BC+</a>]","strongNumber":"G20283","accentedUnicode":"ἐθέλω","relatedNos":[{"strongNumber":"G2309","matchingForm":"θέλω","stepTransliteration":"thelō","gloss":"to will/desire","_zh_tw_Gloss":"願意, 要","_es_Gloss":"querer/desear","_zh_Gloss":"愿意, 要"}],"shortDef":"accustomed","mediumDef":"accustomed","stepGloss":"be willing","stepTransliteration":"ethelō","count":0,"_step_Type":"verb","_stepDetailLexicalTag":"[[\"meaning\",\"G2309\",\"to will/desire\",211,\"θέλω\"],[\"meaning\",\"G20283\",\"be willing\",0,\"ἐθέλω\"]]"}]}